result.text:
I was diagnosed with Acute Myelogenous Leukemia in 2006 ((inv(16)(p12q22)). Chemo protocol failed to keep it in remission. In 2007 I received a Double Cord Stem Cell Transplant (~BMT). Contracted acute & now chronic Graft vs Host Disease post BMT. Melanoma 1A in 2013. This is...

1. Try Not to Get IT in the First Place
Doctors said it was random, but I don't believe so. I worked on oil rigs & despite training hard/eating decent we partied excessively. Drinking, drugging, and long nights of insanity were the norm. The height of the oil boom & my health bust.

This circadian abuse factored into short circuiting my immune system causing it to replicate garbage white blood cells. I arrived at the ER with a WBC over 100,000, very little platelets, & just about dead.

2. Eat Massive Amounts of Protein & Whole Foods
You see a lot of people die on the cancer floors. You also see a lot of people eating garbage foods. I was fortunate to have been a athlete/bodybuilder since HS and grew up eating well. All things being equal, this is paramount.

3. Self-Advocacy Will Save Your Life
The US has the best acute care in the world. Be aggressive & use it. After you live is where they seem to fall short. You will have complications. Doctors are conditioned to treat symptoms with pills & more pills for the side effects. I had a basket of pill bottles, wasting syndrome, & a dead left hip thanks to avascular necrosis caused by high dose prednisone. I eventually titrated off meds myself. I was dying again anyway, so why not on my terms? Strangely enough, I started getting better.

4. SMILE. It can always be worse.
The sad, boo hoo, self pitying patients seem to die a lot. Not saying the good humored don't, but we seem to fare far better. Feeling sorry for yourself is a waste of time & may lead to your demise.

5. Hang Onto Humor
Death is scary. Being a soft, whiny, why me, is even worse. It sucks, but find that silver lining & hold onto it to survive. Laugh, love, & live your life to the absolute fullest because, I promise you, tomorrow is never guaranteed.
